[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-florida-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election** to the United States House of Representatives for Florida's at-large congressional district was held October 6, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-florida-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] The winning candidate would serve a less-than-two-year term in the United States House of Representatives to represent Florida in the 29th Congress from October 6, 1845, to March 4, 1847.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-florida-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] The election was initially called for the Whig candidate, Edward Carrington Cabell, and Cabell was seated in the House of Representatives.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-florida-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] However, a recount found the winner to actually be the Democratic candidate, William Henry Brockenbrough.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-florida-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Brockenbrough was seated immediately on January 24, 1846.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-florida-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] In the 1845 congressional election, David Levy Yulee, a Democrat, was elected to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-florida-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] However, Yulee was jointly elected by the Florida Legislature to the United States Senate, and so resigned from the House of Representatives before taking his seat in order to take his seat in the Senate.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The **1845 United States House of Representatives election in Florida** was held on Monday, May 26, 1845, to elect the first United States Representative from the state of Florida, one from the state's single at-large congressional district, to represent Florida in the 29th Congress.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The election coincided with the elections of other offices, including the gubernatorial election, the senatorial elections, and various state and local elections.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The winning candidate would have served a less-than-two-year term in the United States House of Representatives from July 1, 1845, to March 4, 1847.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] Florida was admitted to the Union as a slave state on March 3, 1845, the last day of the 28th Congress.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The state was not represented in that Congress.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] Florida held its elections on May 26, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] Because Yulee was jointly elected to both the U.S.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] Senate and a person cannot hold both offices at the same time, he resigned from the House before taking his seat.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] A special election was held later in 1845 to elect his replacement, electing Whig Edward Carrington Cabell, though after a recount, Democrat William Henry Brockenbrough was found to be the winner instead.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] The **1844–45 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with James K.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1844 and 1845, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 1.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] The Democratic Party re-captured control of the Senate, gaining a net total of eleven seats from the Whigs.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] In these special elections, the winners were seated during 1844 or in 1845 before March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] In these regular elections, the winners were elected for the term beginning March 4, 1845; ordered by state.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] All of the elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] In these special elections, the winners were elected in 1845 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Reverdy Johnson won election by an unknown margin of votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] There were three elections: Two special elections were held on January 18, 1845, and one regular election was held on February 4, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] The 68th New York State Legislature met from January 7 to May 14, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Tallmadge had been re-elected in 1840 to the Class 1 seat (term 1839–1845), but resigned June 17, 1844, to become Governor of Wisconsin Territory.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] On November 30, Governor of New York William C.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Bouck appointed his Democratic Lieutenant Governor Daniel S.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Dickinson to fill the vacancy temporarily, and Dickinson was seated December 9, 1844.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Silas Wright Jr. had been re-elected in 1843 to the Class 3 seat (term 1843–1849), but resigned November 26, 1844, when elected Governor of New York.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] On November 30, Governor Bouck appointed Democratic State Senator Henry A.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Foster to fill the vacancy temporarily, and Foster took his seat on December 9, 1844.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Dix took his seat on January 27, 1845, and remained in office until March 3, 1849, when his term expired.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Dickinson re-took his seat under the new credentials on January 27, 1845, and re-elected, remained in office until March 3, 1851, when his term expired.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] The regular election was held January 14, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Incumbent Daniel Sturgeon was re-elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the United States Senate.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, convened on January 14, 1845, to elect a Senator to serve the term beginning on March 4, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] A special election was held March 13, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Simon Cameron was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the United States Senate.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Democratic future-U.S. president James Buchanan was elected in an 1834 special election and was re-elected in 1836 and 1843.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Senator Buchanan resigned on March 5, 1845, after being appointed U.S.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Secretary of State by President James K.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1845-united-states-senate-elections-in-florida] Following the resignation of senator Buchanan, the Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on March 13, 1845, to elect a new senator to fill the vacancy and serve the remainder of the term set to expire on March 4, 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1846-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The **1846 United States House of Representatives election in Florida** was held on Monday, October 5, 1846, to elect the single United States Representative from the state of Florida, one from the state's single at-large congressional district, to represent Florida in the 30th Congress.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1846-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The election coincided with the elections of other offices, including various state and local elections.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1846-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The party primaries were held on June 20, 1846.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1846-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The winning candidate would serve a two-year term in the United States House of Representatives from March 4, 1847, to March 4, 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1846-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] A special election was held later in 1845, which saw the election of Edward Carrington Cabell, a Whig.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1846-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] However, his opponent, William Henry Brockenbrough, a Democrat, successfully challenged the results of the election and was seated in the House on January 24, 1846.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The **1848 United States House of Representatives election in Florida** was held on Monday, October 2, 1848, to elect the single United States Representative from the state of Florida, one from the state's single at-large congressional district, to represent Florida in the 31st Congress.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The election coincided with the elections of other offices, including the presidential election, the senatorial election, the gubernatorial election, and various state and local elections.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] The winning candidate would serve a two-year term in the United States House of Representatives from March 4, 1849, to March 4, 1851.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-florida] Despite winning by an extremely small margin in 1846, the coattail effect expanded Cabell's margin in this election.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-presidential-election-in-florida] The **1848 United States presidential election in Florida** took place on November 7, 1848, as part of the 1848 United States presidential election.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-presidential-election-in-florida] Voters chose three representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-presidential-election-in-florida] This was the first time Florida participated in a U.S. presidential election since its admission into the Union on March 3, 1845.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-presidential-election-in-florida] Florida voted for the Whig candidate, Zachary Taylor, over Democratic candidate Lewis Cass.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-presidential-election-in-florida] Taylor won Florida by a margin of 14.40%.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The **1848–49 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1848 and 1849, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The Democratic Party lost seats but maintained control of the Senate.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Note: "Re-elected" includes incumbent appointee elected to the next term.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] In these special elections, the winners were seated during 1848 or in 1849 before March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] In these regular elections, the winners were elected for the term beginning March 4, 1849; ordered by state.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] In these elections, the winners were elected in 1849 after March 4.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Reverdy Johnson won election in 1844 but retired to become the United States Attorney General.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] In order to fill his seat, David Stewart was elected by an unknown margin of votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] James Pearce won re-election by an unknown margin of votes, for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The New York election was held February 6, 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Barnburner John Adams Dix had been elected in 1845 to this seat after the resignation of Silas Wright, and Dix's term would expire on March 3, 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] In November 1848, Dix was the Barnburners/Free-Soilers candidate for Governor of New York, but was defeated by Whig Hamilton Fish.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] At this time New York Democratic Party was split in two fiercely opposing factions: the Barnburners" and the "Hunkers".
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The Barnburners organized the Free Soil Party in 1848 and nominated Martin Van Buren for U.S.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Due to the split, the Whig Party won most of the elective offices by pluralities.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] At the State election in November 1847, 24 Whigs and 8 Democrats were elected for a two-year term (1848–1849) in the State Senate.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] At the State election in November 1848, 106 Whigs, 15 Free Soilers and 7 Hunkers were elected to the Assembly for the session of 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The 72nd New York State Legislature met from January 2 to April 11, 1849, at Albany, New York.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Seward was nominated by a caucus of Whig State legislators on February 1, 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The vote was 88 for Seward, 12 for John A.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Senator John Adams Dix ran for re-election supported by the Free Soilers.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Walworth was the candidate of the Hunkers.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Walworth had been third place in the last gubernatorial election, behind Fish and Dix.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Barnard (Whig) received 2 scattering votes in the Senate.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Seward was the choice of both the Assembly and the Senate, and was declared elected.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The two houses of the Ohio General Assembly met in joint session February 22, 1849, with 72 representatives and 35 senators present to elect a Senator (Class 3) to succeed incumbent William Allen.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The second ballot was declared a nullity by Speaker of the Senate Brewster Randall, because there were one more ballots cast than members present.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The Pennsylvania election was held January 10, 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] James Cooper was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] Incumbent Democrat Simon Cameron, who was elected in 1845, was not a candidate for re-election to another term.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1848-united-states-senate-election-in-florida] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, convened on January 10, 1849, to elect a new Senator to fill the term beginning on March 4, 1849.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] The **1876 United States House of Representatives elections in Florida** were held on November 7 for the 45th Congress.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] These elections were held at the same time as the election for governor and the contentious presidential election, in which Florida was one of four states whose electoral votes were in dispute.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] In the 1874 elections, both Republican incumbents were initially declared re-elected.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] Finley (D) successfully contested the re-election of Josiah T.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] Walls (R), so that at the time of the 1876 elections, Florida had one Democratic and one Republican incumbent.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] Both incumbents ran for re-election, and both were defeated.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] Finley challenged the results of the election in the 2nd district.
[src:1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-florida] On February 20, 1879, Finley was declared the legitimate winner with a vote of 11,329 - 11,077, and was seated in Bisbee's place, serving from February 20, 1879 - March 3, 1879 when the 45th Congress ended.
